    estimatedWordCount: 25000,
    shortDesc: 'The philosophical blueprint for international peace — Kant\'s proposal for a federation of free republics governed by cosmopolitan right, which became the intellectual foundation of the League of Nations, the United Nations, and the European Union.',
    summary: 'Perpetual Peace: A Philosophical Sketch, published in 1795, is Kant\'s most influential work of political philosophy and one of the most consequential political texts of the modern era. Written in the form of an imaginary peace treaty — with preliminary articles, definitive articles, supplements, and appendices — it lays out the conditions under which lasting peace among nations could be achieved. Its proposals were treated as utopian idealism by most of Kant\'s contemporaries; two centuries later, they form the structural foundation of the international legal order.\n\nThe Preliminary Articles specify the immediate conditions that must be met before lasting peace is possible: the prohibition of secret treaty reservations, the prohibition of acquiring states by inheritance or exchange, the gradual abolition of standing armies, the prohibition of national debts for external warfare, the prohibition of hostile interference in the constitution of other states, and the prohibition of conduct in wartime that would make future peace impossible.\n\nThe Definitive Articles establish the positive constitutional requirements. The First requires that every state have a republican constitution — based on the freedom and equality of citizens, the dependence of all on a single legislation, and the separation of executive and legislative powers. Kant argues that republics are inherently more peaceful because citizens who bear the costs of war will be reluctant to vote for it. The Second requires a federation of free states — not a world government (potentially despotic) but a voluntary league of nations committed to settling disputes peacefully. The Third establishes cosmopolitan right — the right of every human being to hospitality on foreign soil, grounded in the common possession of the earth\'s surface.\n\nThe Supplements argue that nature itself — through commercial interdependence, the costs of war to citizens, and the progressive development of republican constitutions — tends toward the conditions of peace, even when human beings do not consciously intend it.',
    themes: ['Perpetual Peace', 'Republican Constitutionalism', 'Federation of Free States', 'Cosmopolitan Right', 'The Abolition of Standing Armies', 'The Prohibition of Colonial Exploitation', 'Unsocial Sociability', 'The Moral Foundations of International Law', 'The Relationship between Morality and Politics'],
