    estimatedWordCount: 4000,
    shortDesc: 'The manifesto of the Enlightenment in four thousand words — Kant\'s definition of intellectual maturity as the courage to think for oneself, and his argument that freedom of public reason is the only condition necessary for human progress.',
    summary: 'What is Enlightenment? — published in the December 1784 issue of the Berlinische Monatsschrift — is the most famous short essay in the history of philosophy and one of the defining texts of Western modernity. In fewer than four thousand words, Kant defines the Enlightenment, diagnoses the obstacles to it, prescribes the conditions for its advancement, and articulates the relationship between intellectual freedom and political authority with a clarity and force that have never been surpassed.\n\nKant\'s definition is lapidary: "Enlightenment is the human being\'s emergence from his self-incurred immaturity." Immaturity (Unmündigkeit) is the inability to use one\'s own understanding without the guidance of another. It is self-incurred when its cause lies not in lack of understanding but in lack of resolution and courage — in the comfortable refusal to think for oneself. The motto of the Enlightenment is therefore "Sapere aude!" — dare to know, dare to use your own reason.\n\nWhy, Kant asks, do so many people remain in a state of intellectual tutelage long after nature has freed them from external direction? His answer is psychologically acute: laziness and cowardice. It is comfortable to be a minor — to let a book think for you, a pastor serve as your conscience, a doctor decide your diet. The "guardians" who have taken charge of the immature majority have every interest in keeping them docile.\n\nThe prescription for enlightenment is freedom — specifically, the freedom to make public use of one\'s reason in all matters. Kant introduces a crucial distinction between the public use of reason and the private use. The public use of reason — the use a scholar makes before the entire reading public — must be unlimited. The private use of reason — the use a person makes in a particular civic post (as a soldier, a pastor, an official) — may be restricted: the soldier must obey orders. But in their capacity as scholars addressing the public, these same individuals must be perfectly free to argue against the orders they obey, the taxes they collect, and the doctrines they preach.',
    themes: ['Enlightenment as Intellectual Maturity', 'The Courage to Think for Oneself', 'Public vs Private Use of Reason', 'Freedom of the Press', 'The Guardians of Immaturity', 'Laziness and Cowardice as Obstacles to Freedom', 'The Progress of the Human Species', 'The Relationship between Philosophy and Political Authority'],
    keyCharacters: [],
