    structure: 'Nine propositions:\n\nFirst: All natural capacities of a creature are destined to develop fully and in conformity with their end\nSecond: In the human being, the natural capacities directed toward the use of reason are to be fully developed only in the species, not in the individual\nThird: Nature has willed that the human being should produce from himself everything beyond mere animal existence\nFourth: The means nature employs is their antagonism in society — unsocial sociability\nFifth: The greatest problem for the human species is the attainment of a universal civil society administering right\nSixth: This problem is the most difficult and the last to be solved — the paradox of the ruler\nSeventh: The problem of a perfect civil constitution depends on the problem of a lawful external relation among states\nEighth: The history of the human species can be regarded as the realization of a hidden plan of nature\nNinth: A philosophical attempt to work out a universal history is possible and may even further nature\'s purpose',
