    estimatedWordCount: 18000,
    shortDesc: 'The hinge of Kant\'s philosophical development — the Latin dissertation in which he first distinguished the sensible from the intelligible world and discovered that space and time are subjective forms of human intuition, opening the decade of silent labour that would produce the Critique of Pure Reason.',
    summary: 'The Inaugural Dissertation — formally titled On the Form and Principles of the Sensible and the Intelligible World — was presented on 21 August 1770 as Kant\'s qualifying dissertation for the position of full Professor of Logic and Metaphysics at the University of Königsberg. It is the most important transitional work in Kant\'s career: the text in which the central insight of the critical philosophy — that space and time are not properties of things in themselves but subjective forms of human sensibility — first appears in print, while the complementary insight — that the categories of the understanding are equally subjective and equally limited to the domain of possible experience — has not yet been achieved.\n\nThe dissertation distinguishes two sources of human cognition: sensibility and the intellect. Sensibility gives us the sensible world — the world of space, time, and material objects as they appear to us. The intellect gives us the intelligible world — the world of things as they are in themselves. The crucial innovation is Kant\'s treatment of space and time. Against Newton, who held that space and time are absolute realities, and against Leibniz, who held that they are systems of relations among things in themselves, Kant argues that space and time are pure forms of sensible intuition — subjective conditions of the human mind that structure all sensory experience but do not apply to things as they are independently of our perception.\n\nHowever, the Inaugural Dissertation retains a position that the first Critique will abandon: the claim that the pure intellect, through its concepts alone, can give us genuine knowledge of the intelligible world — of things as they are in themselves. It was the recognition, sometime during the decade following the Dissertation, that this claim could not be sustained — that the categories of the understanding, like space and time, are valid only within the domain of possible experience — that precipitated the "decade of silence" (1770–1781) and the philosophical revolution of the first Critique.',
