    commentary: [
        { philosopher: 'Karl Ameriks', text: 'Ameriks\'s Kant\'s Theory of Mind (1982) and his subsequent work on the development of Kant\'s philosophy have established the Inaugural Dissertation as the single most important document for understanding the genesis of the critical philosophy. It shows us the moment at which Kant discovered the subjectivity of space and time — the insight that unlocked the first Critique — while still retaining the pre-critical conviction that pure intellect can know things in themselves. The gap between the Dissertation\'s half-revolution and the first Critique\'s complete revolution is the gap that defines the entire critical project, and Ameriks\'s careful tracing of this development has shaped how scholars understand the architecture of Kant\'s mature system.' },
        { philosopher: 'Lewis White Beck', text: 'Beck\'s Early German Philosophy (1969) and his Early Kant essays placed the Inaugural Dissertation in its proper context: the culmination of Kant\'s pre-critical development and the starting gun of his critical transformation. Beck articulated the gap between the Dissertation and the first Critique with characteristic precision: Kant saw in 1770 that sensibility has its own a priori forms; he did not yet see that the intellect is equally limited. The decade of silence is the decade in which this second insight was won — the insight that the categories of the understanding, which the Dissertation treats as giving us access to things in themselves, are in fact valid only within the domain of experience constituted by sensibility.' }
    ],
    modernRelevance: 'The Inaugural Dissertation is of primary interest to Kant scholars and historians of modern philosophy. Its treatment of space and time as subjective forms of intuition is the seed from which the entire critical philosophy grew, and understanding it is essential for understanding what the first Critique accomplishes. The Dissertation\'s argument against both Newtonian absolute space and Leibnizian relational space — in favour of a "third way" that makes space a form of human cognition — continues to be discussed in connection with contemporary philosophy of space and time.',
    context: 'Kant presented the Inaugural Dissertation on 21 August 1770, at the age of forty-six, upon his appointment as full Professor of Logic and Metaphysics. He had previously held the much less prestigious position of Privatdozent. Kant sent copies to several prominent correspondents, including Johann Heinrich Lambert and Moses Mendelssohn, whose responses — particularly Lambert\'s objection that if time is merely subjective, then change itself becomes merely subjective — helped precipitate the decade of silence during which Kant worked out the full critical philosophy. The period from 1770 to 1781 is one of the most productive periods of private philosophical labour in history.',
