    shortDesc: 'Kant\'s most human book — the published version of his most popular lecture course, offering a systematic account of human nature as it actually is: its cognitive faculties, its passions, its vices, its sociability, its national characters, and its destination as a species.',
    summary: 'The Anthropology from a Pragmatic Point of View, published in 1798 as the last book Kant saw through the press, is the most accessible, the most personal, and in many ways the most surprising of his works. It is the published version of the lecture course on anthropology that Kant delivered every winter semester from 1772/73 to 1795/96 — a span of nearly twenty-five years. The Anthropology is "pragmatic" rather than "physiological": it is concerned not with what nature makes of the human being but with what the human being, as a free agent, makes and can make of himself.\n\nThe work is divided into two major parts. The first, "Anthropological Didactic," is a systematic analysis of the human cognitive and affective faculties. Kant draws on a wealth of empirical observation, literary allusion, and personal anecdote that is almost entirely absent from the Critiques. He discusses the nature of dreaming, the phenomenon of genius, the psychology of laughter, the pathology of mental illness, the distinction between temperaments (sanguine, choleric, melancholic, phlegmatic), and the sources of illusion and self-deception. The treatment of the passions is particularly rich: he analyses the three ruling passions of humanity as the desire for honour (ambition), the desire for power (domination), and the desire for possession (avarice).\n\nThe second part, "Anthropological Characteristic," moves from the faculties of the individual to the character of the species. Kant discusses the character of the person, the character of the sexes, the character of nations, and the character of the human race as a whole. The work concludes with a reflection on the "destination of the human species" that connects the empirical anthropology of the lectures with the normative philosophy of history developed in the Idea for a Universal History: the human species is destined to develop from natural barbarism toward a cosmopolitan moral community in which all human capacities are fully realized.',
