    structure: 'Part One: Anthropological Didactic — On the Cognitive Faculty\n\nBook I: On the cognitive faculty — Sense and sensation; inner sense; imagination and memory; wit, acumen, and judgment; the higher cognitive faculties; mental illness\n\nBook II: On the feeling of pleasure and displeasure — Sensible and intellectual pleasure; taste; the nature of laughter\n\nBook III: On the faculty of desire — Affects and passions; the three ruling passions; the moral faculty of desire\n\nPart Two: Anthropological Characteristic — On the Way of Cognizing the Interior of the Human Being from the Exterior\n\nA. The character of the person\nB. The character of the sexes\nC. The character of nations\nD. The character of the race\nE. The character of the species — the destination of the human race',
    quote: 'All the advances in culture by which the human being is educated amount to applying what has been learned and skilfully acquired to the use of the human being in the world. But the most important object in the world to which he can apply this is the human being itself, because it is its own ultimate end.',
