    modernRelevance: 'The Anthropology has experienced a dramatic revival in Kant scholarship since the late twentieth century. Foucault\'s Introduction to Kant\'s Anthropology argued that the anthropological question — "What is the human being?" — is the fundamental question underlying the entire critical philosophy, generating a major secondary literature. Scholars of Kant\'s practical philosophy have recognized that the Anthropology provides the empirical dimension of his ethics — the account of human motivation, self-deception, and moral psychology that the Groundwork and the Critiques presuppose but do not supply. Historians of the human sciences have also identified Kant\'s anthropology lectures as a foundational moment in the development of psychology, sociology, and cultural anthropology as academic disciplines.',
    context: 'Kant delivered his lecture course on anthropology every winter semester from 1772/73 to 1795/96. The published Anthropology of 1798 is based on the lecture notes accumulated over this period, revised and organized for publication. It was the last book he saw through the press; his intellectual powers were declining visibly by 1798. Nevertheless, it remains a rich and rewarding work — the most human of Kant\'s books, and the one in which the philosopher of pure reason reveals himself as a man who spent his life observing, with curiosity, sympathy, and occasional exasperation, the comedy of human nature. Kant died on 12 February 1804, at the age of seventy-nine. His last reported words — "Es ist gut" (It is good) — are perhaps the most Kantian sentence ever spoken.',
